% ============ SUMMARY ============
\newpage
\section*{Summary}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{Summary}

Transposable elements (TEs) are mobile DNA sequences that occupy a substantial fraction of every vertebrate genome. Their accurate annotation underpins comparative genomics and the study of genome evolution, but existing tools rely on alignment to curated reference libraries and on manual curation, which scale poorly with the volume of data now produced by long-read assembly projects and degrade on divergent or lineage-specific families. This project develops deep-learning classifiers trained directly on the Pantera catalogue of approximately 145{,}000 TE consensi from the Vertebrate Genomes Project (VGP), and asks how far convolutional and graph-based representations of raw DNA sequence can replace alignment as the basis for TE classification.

The work is organised as a three-stage narrative around the data split rather than the model. \emph{Stage 1 --- dataset validation}: a tower CNN (v3), a hybrid CNN+GNN (v4) and an early three-class extension (v4.2) are trained on a sequence-level random hold-out. This split allows species to appear in both train and test; high accuracy (v3 binary 91.3\%; v4 binary 93.1\%; v4.2 three-class 98.4\%) is therefore interpreted only as evidence that the Pantera labels carry a learnable signal, with the residual misclassifications used to flag candidate label-noise rather than as a generalisation estimate. \emph{Stage 2 --- species-disjoint outer split}: the same hybrid architecture is retrained with an outer GroupShuffleSplit by species and three amniote genomes (zebra finch, platypus, American alligator) excised entirely as an external benchmark. The inner train/val rotates a 5-fold StratifiedGroupKFold across epochs, so val species cycle back into training over the run; the test set is unaffected because it was excised before the rotation began. v4.3-fix reaches three-class macro $F_1 = 0.982$ and superfamily macro $F_1 = 0.727$ on the species-disjoint Pantera test, but only $F_1 = 0.76$ / $0.23$ on the mini-benchmark. \emph{Stage 3 --- fixed inner split}: the rotating CV is replaced by a single fixed train/val split, so train and val species are disjoint for the whole run. Pantera-test scores fall slightly (cls $F_1 = 0.955$, sf $F_1 = 0.638$) and the mini-benchmark advantage of Stage 2 essentially vanishes (cls $F_1 = 0.61$, sf $F_1 = 0.25$).

Two cross-cutting findings emerge. First, the dominant failure mode is not classical overfitting but \emph{species-shift}: across the three amniote benchmark genomes, top-level class transfer is partial (DNA $F_1$ 0.35--0.81, LTR 0.21--0.50, LINE 0.63--0.71) and the apparent superfamily gain of Stage 2 over Stage 3 is largely an artefact of checkpoint selection on a contaminated validation set. Second, an auxiliary boundary-prediction head trained throughout v1--v4.3 recovers sequence \emph{length} accurately ($r \approx 0.94$) but not absolute canvas position ($r \approx 0.07$--$0.18$); this is a structural consequence of reading from a position-invariant pooled embedding, and motivates a sketched v4.4 successor with sinusoidal position channels and a per-position segmentation head. Saliency on individual misclassifications and semi-supervised contrastive clustering on the v4-era encoder are kept as illustrative sanity checks; both await re-running on the Stage-3 encoder.

