\section{Introduction}

\subsection{Transposable Elements}

% AUDIT(L,C) [L1,C4]: narrowed vertebrate-fraction claim to human; added
% qualifier for other vertebrates.
Transposable elements (TEs) are mobile DNA sequences that propagate copies of themselves within their host genome \cite{mcclintock1950,wells2020field}. Eukaryotic genomes are extensively colonised by TEs: they constitute roughly half of the human genome, with fractions ranging from under 10\% to over 80\% across other vertebrates \cite{wells2020field}, and contribute to chromosomal architecture, gene regulation and species-specific adaptation. Some TE families are autonomous, encoding the enzymes (transposase or reverse transcriptase) required for their own mobilisation; others are non-autonomous, parasitising the machinery of an active autonomous driver \cite{wicker2007unified,wells2020field}.

Knowing which TE families are present in a newly assembled genome, and which copies belong to which family, is a prerequisite for almost every downstream genomic analysis: variant interpretation, comparative genomics, and the study of TE--host coevolution all rely on accurate TE annotation. Existing tools rely on alignment to curated reference libraries together with hand-tuned feature detection and manual curation \cite{smit2015repeatmasker,flynn2020repeatmodeler2}. These approaches scale poorly with the volume of data now produced by long-read assembly projects, and they perform especially badly on divergent or novel families and on non-autonomous elements that are difficult to assign to a driver. A learned classifier that can be trained directly from large catalogues of unannotated insertions would therefore be a valuable complement to alignment-based pipelines.

\subsection{Sequence Features of TE Classes}

The classification task is structured by the biology of how each TE class moves \cite{wicker2007unified,wells2020field}. DNA transposons (Class~II) move by a cut-and-paste mechanism, with autonomous members encoding a transposase that recognises terminal inverted repeats (TIRs) at the boundaries of the element. TIRs are typically 10--50~bp \cite{wicker2007unified}, near-perfect reverse complements of one another, forming a structural signature that a sequence classifier can exploit locally. Class~I elements move via an RNA intermediate. LTR retrotransposons are flanked by direct long terminal repeats (typically 200--600~bp) \cite{wicker2007unified} carrying the regulatory elements for transcription, and internally encode a polyprotein with reverse transcriptase and integrase domains. Long interspersed nuclear elements (LINEs) lack LTRs and instead end with a poly(A) tail; they replicate by target-primed reverse transcription and the autonomous members encode an endonuclease together with a reverse transcriptase.

Two structural features of TE sequences directly constrain the architecture of any classifier. First, a TE may be sequenced from either strand, so a classifier should produce the same prediction for a sequence and its reverse complement (RC). This RC symmetry is a hard constraint that is most cleanly imposed inside the model rather than via test-time augmentation. Second, a TIR is by definition a reverse-complement match between the two ends of the element \cite{wicker2007unified}; detecting it requires comparing positions that may be several kilobases apart in a sequence whose total length varies by two orders of magnitude across families.

\subsection{Previous Work and the Pantera Catalogue}

The most widely used tool for TE annotation, RepeatMasker \cite{smit2015repeatmasker}, identifies repeats by aligning a query genome against a curated library such as Dfam \cite{storer2021dfam} or Repbase. Its output is therefore only as good as the underlying library: divergent or lineage-specific families are missed or systematically misclassified. Several recent efforts have applied machine learning to TE detection or sub-classification\,---\,including deep-learning classifiers such as DeepTE \cite{yan2020deepte} and TERL \cite{requena2021terl}; however, most have either focused on a single TE class or been trained on the same curated reference libraries they are meant to extend, limiting their ability to generalise to novel or lineage-specific families.

The starting point for this project is the Pantera catalogue, which uses pangenome polymorphisms to detect TE insertions that are absent in some haplotypes of a species \cite{sierra2024pantera}. Applied to the Vertebrate Genomes Project (VGP) assemblies \cite{rhie2021vgp}, Pantera produces a catalogue of approximately 145{,}000 sequences from over fifty vertebrate species, with FASTA-header annotations giving the broad TE class (DNA, LTR, LINE, SINE, RC, \dots) and, where assignable, the superfamily. Because Pantera detects elements directly from polymorphism, it provides an unusually large, alignment-independent training set on which a learned classifier can be built without circularly inheriting the biases of a reference library. The dataset is, however, heavily skewed: roughly 92\% of sequences carry no transposase annotation, DNA transposons constitute only about 8\%, and many superfamilies have fewer than a hundred examples.

\subsection{Convolutional Neural Networks for Sequence Classification}

Convolutional neural networks (CNNs) \cite{lecun2015deep,krizhevsky2012imagenet,alipanahi2015deepbind} are a natural choice for detecting short, position-invariant motifs in biological sequences. A 1-D convolution over a one-hot-encoded sequence learns a bank of filters whose activations indicate where in the sequence each motif occurs; stacking convolutions with non-linearities then composes these motifs into longer patterns. Two architectural ingredients matter for TE sequences in particular. \emph{Multi-scale} convolutions, with several kernel widths in parallel, allow the network to capture both short, locally conserved motifs and longer structural features in the same forward pass. \emph{Dilated} convolutions enlarge the receptive field exponentially with depth without an equivalent growth in parameters \cite{yu2016dilated}, which is necessary to span TIRs whose two halves may be several kilobases apart.

CNNs also have well-known limitations. After global pooling, all positional information is averaged out, so a CNN-only classifier cannot directly use absolute or relative position within the sequence. Within the receptive field of a given filter, the precise spatial layout of nucleotides is preserved, but anything more global must be re-learned from indirect cues such as motif density.

\subsection{Graph Neural Networks for Compositional Information}\label{ssec:gnn_intro}

A complementary view of a TE sequence is its $k$-mer composition: the multiset of all length-$k$ substrings, which captures global compositional bias and many long-range correlations that motif filters do not see. Even a logistic regression on canonical 7-mer frequencies separates the three top-level classes (DNA, LTR, LINE) at roughly 85\% macro $F_1$ (Section~\ref{ssec:stage2}; Figure~\ref{fig:kmer_separation}), establishing that compositional signal alone is highly informative for class-level identification. However, a single global $k$-mer histogram discards positional structure entirely, and a fixed positional binning would tie the representation to a particular sequence length.

A graph neural network (GNN) \cite{kipf2016semi,hamilton2017inductive,zhou2019graph} provides a flexible compromise. The sequence is broken into overlapping windows; each window contributes a node whose feature vector is its windowed $k$-mer profile, and adjacent windows are connected by edges. Message passing then mixes information between neighbouring windows over several layers, producing a global representation that retains coarse positional structure without requiring fixed-length input. Using \emph{canonical} $k$-mers (the lexicographically smaller of a $k$-mer and its reverse complement) keeps the representation strand-symmetric.

\subsection{Attention Fusion and Hierarchical Heads}

CNN and GNN branches see complementary aspects of the same sequence: the CNN sees local motifs, the GNN sees windowed composition. An attention-style gating layer \cite{vaswani2017attention} learns a per-input convex combination of the two branch embeddings, so that the fused representation can lean on whichever modality is locally more informative. The downstream classifier is hierarchical: a top-level head (binary DNA/non-DNA, or three-way DNA/LTR/LINE) is paired with a superfamily head, mirroring both the biological taxonomy and the empirical observation that top-level discrimination is intrinsically easier than fine-grained superfamily assignment.

This thesis develops these ideas as a three-stage narrative organised around the data split rather than the model architecture. After describing the data, model family and three-stage protocol (Section~\ref{sec:methods}), Section~\ref{sec:results} reports: a TIR-detection CNN as a sequence-only proof of concept (v1); a Stage-1 dataset audit using v3 (CNN), v4 (hybrid binary) and v4.2 (hybrid three-class) on a sequence-level random hold-out, treated as a label-quality check rather than a generalisation estimate; a Stage-2 species-disjoint outer split with rotating-CV inner train/val (v4.2-fix, v4.3-fix), which gives the first cross-species test numbers on a held-out set of VGP species; and a Stage-3 fixed inner split (v4.3-singlefold) that further removes the train/val species overlap induced by the rotating CV. The same three Stage-2/3 models are evaluated on a mini-benchmark of three excised amniote genomes (zebra finch, platypus, American alligator) to estimate transfer to truly unseen species. Two interpretability analyses --- gradient-based saliency and semi-supervised contrastive clustering --- are reported on the v4-era encoder as illustrative sanity checks, with re-running on the Stage-3 encoder flagged as future work.

% ============ DATA AND METHODS ============
\newpage
\section{Data and Methods}\label{sec:methods}

\subsection{Data}\label{ssec:data}

The training data are transposable element sequences identified by Pantera \cite{sierra2024pantera} from the Vertebrate Genomes Project (VGP) assemblies. Pantera detects TE families directly from pangenome polymorphisms by identifying insertions present in some haplotypes and absent in others, and therefore produces a comprehensive catalogue of TEs without inheriting the family list of any particular reference library. The catalogue used here contains approximately 145{,}000 sequences from over fifty vertebrate species. 

In particular, the dataset includes 11{,}500 TIR-positive sequences that are used to train the v1 TIR-detection model. The full set of sequences, with class and superfamily labels parsed from the FASTA headers, is used for the v3 and v4 models. The v4.3 three-class model and the external benchmark (Section~\ref{ssec:mini_benchmark}) use a subset of the full set with only DNA, LTR and LINE classes. 

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\begin{subfigure}[t]{0.42\textwidth}
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{superfamily_class_distribution.png}
  \caption{Top-level class distribution across 135{,}751 TE sequences in the dataset. Unannotated sequences  dominate at 62.3\%. Among annotated classes LTR (18.8\%), LINE (10.4\%) and DNA (7.9\%) are the principal categories, while minor classes (SINE, PLE, RC $<$0.5\%) contribute to less than 0.5\%. }
  \label{fig:class_distribution}
\end{subfigure}%
\hfill
\begin{subfigure}[t]{0.55\textwidth}
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{superfamily_distribution_bar.png}
  \caption{Superfamily abundances within each top-level class (top 30, excluding None). LTR/Gypsy and LINE/L1 are the most frequent. Among DNA transposons, hAT and TcMar-Tc1 dominate; rare superfamilies (${<}200$ samples) are the main source of fine-grained classification difficulty.}
  \label{fig:superfamily_distribution}
\end{subfigure}
\caption{Dataset class and superfamily distribution. The severe class imbalance motivates the subsampling strategy used to balance binary classification heads and the inverse square-root loss weighting applied at the superfamily level.}
\label{fig:dataset_distribution}
\end{figure}

The class distribution is heavily imbalanced: unannotated sequences (``None'') dominate at 62.3\%, with LTR (18.8\%), LINE (10.4\%) and DNA (7.9\%) as the major labelled classes (Figure~\ref{fig:dataset_distribution}). Within DNA, only seven superfamilies exceed 100 examples; counts span 4{,}900 (DNA/hAT) to 129 (DNA/Maverick). Sequence lengths range from 173~bp to 19{,}907~bp (median 3{,}263~bp). 

\paragraph{External mini-benchmark.} For the cross-species evaluations carried out at Stages 2 and 3 (Section~\ref{ssec:splits}), three species are excised from the VGP pool entirely --- removed from both training and validation --- and reserved as an external held-out benchmark: Zebra finch (\textit{Taeniopygia guttata}, Aves), platypus (\textit{Ornithorhynchus anatinus}, Mammalia) and American alligator (\textit{Alligator mississippiensis}, Reptilia). The three species span the main amniote lineages; for each, a mini-benchmark dataset was assembled from three complementary sources: (i)~Pantera-derived consensus sequences from that species' genome, (ii)~an externally curated RepeatMasker-format TE reference library carrying \texttt{Name\#Class/Subclass} annotations, and (iii)~a set of structurally detected LTR retrotransposons produced by genome-wide alignment of LTR terminal repeats. The Stage-2 and Stage-3 mini-benchmark evaluations (Section~\ref{ssec:mini_benchmark}) use the curated libraries as the primary ground-truth set; the Pantera consensi and structural LTR sequences are additional reference data. The Stage-1 dataset audit (Section~\ref{ssec:stage1}) does \emph{not} apply this exclusion --- by design, since its goal is to surface mislabelled examples across the full catalogue, not to estimate generalisation.

\subsection{Sequence Representation}\label{ssec:repr}

All models take one-hot encoded DNA sequences as input. Each nucleotide is mapped to one of five channels (A, C, G, T, N), where N covers ambiguous or non-standard bases. Channels are stacked along the feature dimension to produce a tensor of shape (5, $L$). 

Because CNNs require a fixed input length, every sequence is placed on a fixed-length canvas ( 20~kb by default). In each epoch, for a sequence of length $\ell$, a start position $s$ is sampled uniformly from $\{0, 1, \dots, L-\ell\}$, the sequence occupies positions $s$ through $s+\ell-1$, and the rest of the canvas is filled with zero columns. A binary mask records which positions carry real sequence; the mask is consumed by the masked global pooling layer so that padded positions do not contribute to the pooled embedding. Random placement during training also serves as positional augmentation: the model sees each sequence at many different absolute offsets across epochs.

Reverse-complement invariance is built into the encoding. The reverse complement of a one-hot tensor is obtained by reversing the spatial axis and remapping channels (A$\leftrightarrow$T, C$\leftrightarrow$G); this is a deterministic operation that adds no new parameters. Both the forward and the reverse-complement views of a sequence are passed through the encoder during the forward pass and fused for later embeddings (Section~\ref{ssec:methods_family}).

\subsection{Model v1: TIR Detection CNN}\label{ssec:methods_v1}

The v1 model is a binary classifier for TIR presence and serves as a sequence-only proof of concept that the encoder family used in subsequent models can detect a structural TE feature directly from raw sequence. Cross-species generalisation is not in scope here: the v1 split is a sequence-level random hold-out (no species grouping), since the task is to demonstrate that a balanced TIR / non-TIR boundary is learnable in principle. Cross-species evaluation is introduced for the multi-class models from Section~\ref{ssec:splits} onward.

The CNN encoder uses three parallel branches (kernel widths 7, 15, 21~bp; 128 feature maps each), concatenated and mixed by a $1\!\times\!1$ convolution, then followed by four dilated convolutional blocks (kernel size 9; dilation rates 1, 2, 4, 8; GELU, batch normalisation, dropout 0.15, residual). A masked global average pool produces a 128-dimensional embedding. RC invariance is achieved by late fusion: both the forward and RC-strand embeddings are averaged before the binary head.

\subsection{Classification Model Family}\label{ssec:methods_family}

The TIR detector (v1) above and the classifiers used at every stage below share the same encoder backbone and a small set of optional extensions. This subsection describes the family once; the differences between v3, v4, v4.2, v4.3 and v4.3-singlefold are then differences only in (i) the head (binary vs three-way; 7 vs 23 superfamilies), (ii) the data split (Section~\ref{ssec:splits}), and in two cases (iii) the presence of the GNN branch.

\paragraph{CNN tower (v3 onward).} The pooled 128-dim embedding from the v1 encoder (Section~\ref{ssec:methods_v1}) is fed into a hierarchical pair of heads: a top-level head (binary DNA vs non-DNA in v3 and v4; three-way DNA/LTR/LINE in v4.2 onward) and a superfamily head, jointly trained with the superfamily loss masked out for examples whose top-level label falls outside the superfamily vocabulary.

\paragraph{Hybrid CNN+GNN (v4 onward).} The v4 hybrid model adds a parallel $k$-mer GNN branch alongside the CNN tower. The sequence is tiled into 512~bp windows with stride 256~bp (50\% overlap); each window is represented by its canonical 7-mer histogram (canonical $k$-mers being the lexicographically smaller of a $k$-mer and its reverse complement, which keeps the representation strand-symmetric), hashed into a fixed 2048-dim feature vector, and concatenated with a short relative positional encoding. The windows form the nodes of a chain graph with bidirectional edges between adjacent windows and self-loops; a 3-layer GraphSAGE-style \cite{hamilton2017inductive} GNN with hidden dimension 128 then aggregates information across neighbouring windows, and a scatter-mean pool produces a single 128-dim graph-level embedding. The CNN and GNN embeddings are fused by an attention gate: a small MLP takes the concatenation of the two and outputs a two-element softmax, giving a per-input convex combination of the two branches. The fused embedding is then fed to the same hierarchical heads as v3.

\paragraph{Three-class extensions (v4.2, v4.3, v4.3-singlefold).} The hybrid architecture is unchanged; only the top-level head is broadened from binary to three-way (DNA / LTR / LINE) and the superfamily head from 7 to 23 outputs. Sequences with rare or ambiguous classes (SINE 0.42\%, PLE 0.20\%, RC 0.12\%) and unannotated sequences are excluded from training and evaluation; 50{,}431 sequences across 23 superfamilies remain. Each superfamily is capped at 3{,}000 sequences (\texttt{MAX\_PER\_SF}) for training, giving an effective training pool of 30{,}727 sequences.

\paragraph{Boundary-prediction auxiliary head.} A two-layer MLP (128$\to$64$\to$3, GELU, sigmoid) on the pooled embedding predicts the normalised start, end and length of the real sequence on the canvas, trained with MSE at loss-weight 0.1. It acts as a regulariser by encouraging the encoder to retain enough spatial information to recover sequence placement; as discussed in Section~\ref{ssec:tir} and Section~\ref{ssec:limitations}, length is recoverable but absolute canvas position is not.

\paragraph{Contrastive embedding head (v5).} For the semi-supervised clustering analysis in Section~\ref{ssec:clustering}, the pretrained v4 hybrid encoder is reused: the classification head is replaced by a 128-dim $\ell_2$-normalised projection head, and the encoder is fine-tuned with a combined loss
\[
\mathcal{L}_{\text{total}} = \mathcal{L}_{\text{SupCon}} + \lambda_{\text{cls}} \cdot \mathcal{L}_{\text{CE}} + \lambda_{\text{ctr}} \cdot \mathcal{L}_{\text{center}}
\]
where $\mathcal{L}_{\text{SupCon}}$ is the supervised contrastive loss \cite{khosla2020supervised} ($\tau = 0.3$), $\mathcal{L}_{\text{CE}}$ is cross-entropy over the DNA superfamilies that anchors the embedding to the known label structure and prevents collapse, and $\mathcal{L}_{\text{center}}$ pulls embeddings toward learned per-class centroids ($\lambda_{\text{cls}} = 0.5$, $\lambda_{\text{ctr}} = 0.01$). After training, 256-dim fused embeddings are projected to 2-D with UMAP and clustered with HDBSCAN.

\subsection{Three-Stage Data Splits}\label{ssec:splits}

The same model family is trained three times under progressively stricter data-split regimes, and the comparisons across stages are the central evidence in the Results. Table~\ref{tab:splits} summarises the protocol; the stages are described below.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\small
\begin{tabular}{llll}
\toprule
& Stage 1 (audit) & Stage 2 (species-disjoint) & Stage 3 (fixed inner) \\
\midrule
Outer train/test split & sequence-level random 80/20 & GroupShuffleSplit, group=species, & same as Stage 2 \\
                       &                              & test=20\%, seed=42; \texttt{EXCLUDE\_GENOMES} & \\
Inner train/val split & random within trainval & rotating StratifiedGroupKFold $k=5$ & GroupShuffleSplit \\
                      &                         & seed=42, fold $=$ epoch $\bmod\, 5$ & seed=43, val=20\% \\
Models trained        & v3, v4, v4.2 (baseline) & v4.2-fix, v4.3-fix & v4.3-singlefold \\
Train/val species disjoint? & --- & no (val species recycle into train) & yes (val species frozen) \\
Train/test species disjoint? & no (species overlap) & yes (test species disjoint) & yes \\
Reported in   & §\ref{ssec:stage1} & §\ref{ssec:stage2} & §\ref{ssec:stage3} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{The three-stage data-split protocol. \texttt{EXCLUDE\_GENOMES} = \{\textit{T.~guttata}, \textit{O.~anatinus}, \textit{A.~mississippiensis}\} are removed from the VGP pool entirely at Stages~2 and 3 and held out as the mini-benchmark; Stage~1 uses the full pool. The Stage-2 inner CV cycles each fold's val species back into training across epochs, so val metrics inflate as the run progresses, while the test set is unaffected because the test species were excised before any rotation began.}
\label{tab:splits}
\end{table}

\paragraph{Stage 1 --- dataset audit (v3, v4, v4.2 baseline).} The split unit is the individual sequence; class-balancing (subsample non-DNA to 20{,}000 for v3/v4; \texttt{MAX\_PER\_SF}=3000 for v4.2) is applied \emph{before} a random 80/20 hold-out. This split allows species (and frequently near-identical Pantera consensi from the same species) to appear in both train and test, so high test scores are inflated relative to a species-stratified or naturally distributed evaluation. The intended use of Stage~1 is therefore not to estimate generalisation but to perform a \emph{label audit}: under this split a learned classifier should reproduce the labels almost everywhere if those labels carry any consistent signal, and the residual misclassifications then become candidates for relabelling or curation. This is the same logic used in confident-learning approaches to dataset cleaning \cite{northcutt2021confident}, and in the established practice within RepeatMasker / Dfam pipelines of cycling self-classification through curation \cite{storer2021dfam,flynn2020repeatmodeler2}.

\paragraph{Stage 2 --- species-disjoint outer split (v4.2-fix, v4.3-fix).} The outer test set is drawn by GroupShuffleSplit with group~=~species (random\_state=42, test\_size=0.2), so the 20\% test set comes from species that never appear in trainval. The mini-benchmark species (Section~\ref{ssec:data}) are additionally excised from the trainval pool. Inside trainval, train and val are formed by a 5-fold StratifiedGroupKFold (random\_state=42), with the active val fold cycled per epoch (\texttt{fold = (epoch-1) mod 5}). Within any single epoch train and val are species-disjoint, but across the run every val species rotates into training, so val metrics inflate to near-perfect by late epochs. The test set is unaffected because the test species were excised before any rotation began. The two checkpoints reported are v4.2-fix (epoch 28; \texttt{MAX\_PER\_SF}=5000) and v4.3-fix (epoch 40; \texttt{MAX\_PER\_SF}=3000, \texttt{EXCLUDE\_GENOMES} applied).

\paragraph{Stage 3 --- single-fold inner split (v4.3-singlefold).} The outer test split is identical to Stage~2. The rotating inner CV is replaced by a single fixed GroupShuffleSplit on trainval (random\_state=43, val\_size=0.2), so train and val species are disjoint for the whole run and the val metrics are no longer inflated by the inner-CV rotation (they plateau at $\sim$0.67--0.70 sf macro $F_1$ rather than 0.99). Best checkpoint is epoch 28. This is the most stringent split used in the project and provides the most conservative estimate of generalisation to truly unseen species when combined with the mini-benchmark.

\subsection{Training}\label{ssec:training}

All models are trained with cross-entropy losses (label smoothing $\alpha = 0.1$ on multi-class heads; inverse square-root class weighting on the superfamily head) and the boundary-regression auxiliary loss at weight 0.1. Training uses early stopping on validation macro $F_1$ with patience 10 epochs, with the additional cap of 40 epochs on the v4.x multi-class runs to limit the overfitting documented in Section~\ref{ssec:stage1}. The CNN-only models (v3) use batch size 32; hybrid models (v4 onward) use batch size 16 because of the additional GNN-branch memory --- a known confound when comparing v3 and v4 head-to-head. Optimiser, learning rate and schedule details are listed in the hyperparameter table (Table~\ref{tab:hyperparams}). Five-fold cross-validation was used during model development to guide hyperparameter selection; all reported test scores are single-split point estimates and do not carry standard errors.

\subsection{Evaluation}\label{ssec:evaluation}

Three test sets recur throughout the Results, with the assignment determined by stage. The \emph{Stage-1 random hold-out} is a sequence-level 20\% slice of the (class-balanced) Pantera pool and is used only for the dataset-audit comparisons in Section~\ref{ssec:stage1}. The \emph{Stage-2 / Stage-3 species-disjoint Pantera test} is a 20\% slice of VGP species held out under the species-grouped outer split, and is the primary in-distribution generalisation metric for the multi-class models. The \emph{mini-benchmark} on the three excised amniote genomes is the headline external metric for Stages~2 and~3 (Section~\ref{ssec:mini_benchmark}). Reported metrics are accuracy, macro and weighted $F_1$, and per-class $F_1$; AUROC and AUPRC for binary tasks; and separate top-level and superfamily scores for hierarchical models. Per-superfamily $F_1$ is reported only for superfamilies with $\geq$30 test samples. For the mini-benchmark, FASTA headers are mapped to the model vocabulary by exact superfamily match, parent-class fallback, or exclusion; sequences outside the three-way head (SINE, RC/Helitron, Unknown) are excluded.

\subsection{Implementation}\label{ssec:implementation}

All models were implemented in PyTorch 2.0+ and trained either locally on Apple-silicon MPS or on NVIDIA A100 GPU on CSD3 (Cambridge Service for Data Driven Discovery). Training and inference use full-precision FP32; validation losses, validation macro $F_1$ and the learned attention gate weights are logged each epoch and used to drive early stopping. The hyperparameter values used for all models are summarised in Table~\ref{tab:hyperparams}. 

