\subsubsection{Hybrid CNN + k-mer GNN (v4, binary)}\label{ssec:hybrid}

The v4 hybrid model (Section~\ref{ssec:methods_family}) augments the CNN tower with a parallel windowed $k$-mer GNN branch and fuses the two embeddings through a learned attention gate, aiming to capture positional and compositional information. It is evaluated first in the same binary (DNA vs non-DNA) setting as v3, then extended to a three-class head in v4.2 / v4.3 (Section~\ref{ssec:v42_baseline}). 

In the binary setting, the learned gate weights remain highly variable throughout training and no branch consistently dominates (Figure~\ref{fig:v4_training}, lower-left panel), suggesting that the model does not prefer a fixed CNN-vs-GNN split for the binary task. Gate weight behaviour differs markedly in the three-class extension: see Figure~\ref{fig:gate_weights} and Section~\ref{ssec:hybrid_disc}. 

\paragraph{Comparison with the CNN-only baseline.}

The hybrid model improves on the CNN-only baseline on both tasks (Table~\ref{tab:v3_v4_sf_f1}; Figure~\ref{fig:v4_confusion}). Binary accuracy rises from 91.3\,\% to 93.1\,\% (macro $F_1$ 0.87\,$\to$\,0.89). For DNA superfamily classification, macro $F_1$ rises from 0.91 to 0.96, with the gain almost entirely in DNA/CMC ($F_1$ 0.67\,$\to$\,0.92): the GNN's $k$-mer composition signal provides the additional discriminant that resolves CMC confusion with generic-DNA sequences. A standalone $k$-mer GNN achieves AUROC\,=\,0.905 for binary DNA detection but only 41\,\% balanced accuracy across individual classes, confirming that global composition encodes class-level but not superfamily-level information (Section~\ref{ssec:stage2}).

