\label{fig:v4_training}
\end{figure}

\subsubsection{Three-Class Baseline (v4.2)}\label{ssec:v42_baseline}

Extending the hybrid head from binary to three-way (DNA / LTR / LINE) and from 7 to 23 superfamilies (architecture details in Section~\ref{ssec:methods_family}) gives the v4.2 baseline. Under the Stage-1 random split, validation superfamily macro $F_1$ reaches 1.000 by epoch 65 while the held-out test superfamily $F_1$ is only 0.872 (Table~\ref{tab:v4_2_splits}). The top-level head generalises essentially perfectly (test class macro $F_1 = 0.984$, gap 0.016), but the superfamily gap of 0.127 is the first quantitative signal that the random split is fitting genome- and species-specific subvariants of rare superfamilies ($n < 500$ training samples) rather than a generalisable superfamily signature. The 65-epoch training trajectory in Figure~\ref{fig:v4_2_training} shows this directly: training loss plateaus around 0.44 while val class and val sf $F_1$ both rise monotonically to $>0.99$, the classical signature of a leaky split.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lcccc}
\hline
Split & $N$ & Class accuracy & Class macro $F_1$ & SF macro $F_1$ \\
\hline
Train & 19{,}665 & 1.000 & 1.000 & 0.999 \\
Val   &  4{,}916 & 1.000 & 1.000 & 1.000 \\
Test  &  6{,}146 & 0.984 & 0.984 & 0.872 \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\caption{v4.2 split-level performance at epoch 65 (best Stage-1 checkpoint). The val/test gap of 0.127 at the superfamily level under a random split prompts the species-disjoint protocols of Stages 2 and 3.}
\label{tab:v4_2_splits}
\end{table}

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{v4_2_training.png}
\caption{Training trajectory for v4.2 (Stage-1 random split, 65 epochs). Left: training loss. Centre: validation class and superfamily macro $F_1$ both rise monotonically to near-perfect values, while held-out test sf $F_1 = 0.872$ --- the classical signature of a leaky split. The red dashed line marks epoch 40, adopted as the training cap for v4.3-fix and v4.3-singlefold. Right: attention-gate weights, with CNN dominating at $\approx 0.88$.}
\label{fig:v4_2_training}
\end{figure}

\paragraph{Stage 1 takeaways.} The Stage-1 results across v3, v4 and v4.2 are internally consistent: top-level class boundaries (DNA vs non-DNA in v3/v4; DNA / LTR / LINE in v4.2) are recovered at $>$98\% accuracy, while fine-grained superfamily $F_1$ drops as the head broadens (v3 7-way 0.90; v4 7-way 0.96; v4.2 23-way 0.872). Read as a label audit (Section~\ref{ssec:splits}), Stage~1 confirms that the Pantera labels carry strong learnable signal at the class level and that the residual superfamily confusions are concentrated on small, heterogeneous superfamilies (DNA/CMC, LINE/L1-Tx1) and on the generic-class catch-all (\textit{DNA}, \textit{LTR}). Two refinements are carried into Stages~2 and~3: (i)~capping training at 40 epochs, beyond which the val/test gap had already widened in v4.2, and (ii)~replacing the random split with a species-grouped outer split.

\subsection{Stage 2 --- Species-Disjoint Outer Split with Rotating-CV Inner (v4.3-fix)}\label{ssec:stage2}

\subsubsection{Protocol and Train/Val Leak Caveat}

Stage~2 retrains the same hybrid architecture under the protocol of Section~\ref{ssec:splits}: an outer GroupShuffleSplit by species reserves 21 species ($\approx 11$k sequences) as a species-disjoint test set, and three additional species (\textit{T.~guttata}, \textit{O.~anatinus}, \textit{A.~mississippiensis}) are excised entirely as the mini-benchmark (Section~\ref{ssec:mini_benchmark}). Inside the remaining 86 trainval species, a 5-fold StratifiedGroupKFold rotates the val fold each epoch (\texttt{fold = (epoch-1) mod 5}). Two checkpoints are reported: v4.2-fix (epoch 28; \texttt{MAX\_PER\_SF}=5000, no \texttt{EXCLUDE\_GENOMES}) and v4.3-fix (epoch 40; \texttt{MAX\_PER\_SF}=3000 + \texttt{EXCLUDE\_GENOMES}). The outer test split is uncontaminated --- those 21 species never appear in trainval --- but the inner rotating CV cycles every val species through training across the run, so the val metrics inflate to $\approx$1.0 by late epochs and become unreliable for early stopping. The Stage-3 single-fold inner split (Section~\ref{ssec:stage3}) addresses this.

\subsubsection{Performance on Species-Disjoint Pantera Test}

On the species-disjoint Pantera test set, v4.3-fix reaches three-class macro $F_1 = 0.982$ (accuracy 98.4\%) and superfamily macro $F_1 = 0.727$ over 23 superfamilies; v4.2-fix reaches class $F_1 = 0.895$ / sf $F_1 = 0.604$. All three top-level classes are well separated under v4.3-fix (DNA $F_1 = 0.978$, LTR $0.990$, LINE $0.978$). Per-superfamily $F_1$ on the test split is highest for LINE families (LINE/L1 $0.96$, LINE/CR1 $\approx 0.99$) and for the largest DNA superfamily (DNA/hAT $0.92$); the generic LTR catch-all label remains the hardest single superfamily ($F_1 \approx 0.33$). The 0.92 DNA/hAT score is, however, qualified by Stage~3 (Section~\ref{ssec:stage3}): once the inner train/val rotation is removed, this score collapses to $\approx 0.26$, so the Stage-2 hAT number is best read as an upper bound that depended on the contaminated validation set rather than as a stable test-set result.

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{v4_3_confusion.png}
\caption{Confusion matrices for v4.3-fix on the species-disjoint Pantera test set: three-class (left) and the ten most abundant superfamilies (right). Top-level separation is near-perfect; superfamily confusions concentrate within-class.}
\label{fig:v4_3_confusion}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{gate_weights.png}
\caption{Attention-gate weights over Stage-2 v4.3-fix training. The GNN branch converges to weight $\approx 0.72$ from $\approx$ epoch 25, the reverse of the CNN-dominant pattern seen in v4 binary (Section~\ref{ssec:hybrid}) and in v4.2 baseline (Figure~\ref{fig:v4_2_training} right). When the head distinguishes three mechanistically distinct top-level classes, global $k$-mer composition becomes the more informative branch (cf.~Section~\ref{ssec:hybrid_disc}).}
\label{fig:gate_weights}
\end{figure}

\paragraph{$k$-mer features dominate the three-class head.} A standalone $k$-mer baseline supports this gate-weight pattern: 5-fold CV on canonical 7-mer frequencies gives a logistic regression macro $F_1 = 0.855 \pm 0.010$ for the top-level three-class task and a random forest $F_1 = 0.848 \pm 0.015$ (Figure~\ref{fig:kmer_separation}), substantially above the majority-class baseline. Within a top-level class, the same features collapse to near-chance for superfamily discrimination ($F_1$ 0.064--0.097 for $k=5$; Table~\ref{tab:kmer_within_class}). Compositional signals therefore provide a strong prior for class identity, on which the GNN branch can lean, while fine-grained superfamily separation is driven entirely by the CNN tower.

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{kmer_separation.png}
\caption{Standalone $k$-mer baseline for top-level three-class classification (DNA/LTR/LINE): logistic regression and random forest on canonical 7-mer frequencies reach macro $F_1 \approx 0.85$ under 5-fold CV. This justifies the GNN branch of the hybrid architecture.}
\label{fig:kmer_separation}
\end{figure}

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lccc}
\toprule
TE class & \# superfamilies & macro $F_1$ (LR, $k$=5) \\
\midrule
DNA & 11 & 0.064 \\
LTR & 7  & 0.094 \\
LINE & 7 & 0.097 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Within-class superfamily discrimination using canonical $k$-mer frequencies ($k$=5, 5-fold CV, 2000-per-class cap). Near-chance performance confirms that fine-grained classification is driven by the CNN branch, not by $k$-mer composition.}
\label{tab:kmer_within_class}
\end{table}

\subsection{Stage 3 --- Single-Fold Inner Split (v4.3-singlefold)}\label{ssec:stage3}

\subsubsection{Removing the Train/Val Species Overlap}

Stage~3 keeps the same outer species-disjoint test split as Stage~2 but replaces the rotating 5-fold inner CV with a single fixed GroupShuffleSplit (random\_state=43, val=20\%) on the 86 trainval species. Train and val species are now disjoint for the entire run, so the val metrics are no longer inflated by the rotating-CV schedule: validation superfamily $F_1$ plateaus at $\approx 0.67$--$0.70$ rather than 0.99. The best v4.3-singlefold checkpoint is epoch 28.

\subsubsection{Performance on Species-Disjoint Pantera Test}

On the same species-disjoint Pantera test set used in Stage~2, v4.3-singlefold reaches class macro $F_1 = 0.955$ (accuracy 95.9\%) and superfamily macro $F_1 = 0.638$ (Table~\ref{tab:stage_compare}). Compared with Stage~2 v4.3-fix, the class $F_1$ drops by 0.027 ($0.982 \to 0.955$) and the superfamily $F_1$ by 0.089 ($0.727 \to 0.638$). The val$\to$test gap also collapses: v4.3-singlefold's Stage-3 val sf $F_1$ ($\approx 0.696$) is within 0.06 of its test ($0.638$), versus Stage~2's val $\approx 0.99$ vs test $0.727$ (gap $\approx 0.26$), which suggests that the apparent Stage-2 superfamily strength was largely a side-effect of the inner-CV rotation rather than a real generalisation gain.

\paragraph{The DNA/hAT collapse.} The most striking single change between Stage~2 and Stage~3 is on DNA/hAT, the largest DNA superfamily ($n \approx 1100$ on the test split): test $F_1$ falls from $0.919$ (v4.3-fix) to $0.256$ (v4.3-singlefold). The v4.2-fix Stage-2 checkpoint shows the same collapse on hAT ($F_1 = 0.265$), so the 0.92 score was attainable only because the rotating CV recycled hAT-rich val species back into training, and is not an architectural property. Both leak-controlled variants land within $0.01$ of each other on hAT ($\approx 0.26$), suggesting hAT --- an extremely diverse superfamily with strong overlap with the generic-DNA catch-all label --- is at the limit of what a 23-way flat softmax can resolve from sequence alone (Section~\ref{ssec:limitations}). This pattern is the dominant contributor to the $\Delta$ sf macro $F_1 = 0.089$ between Stages~2 and~3.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\small
\begin{tabular}{lcccccc}
\toprule
Stage & Variant & Cls acc & Cls macro $F_1$ & SF macro $F_1$ & DNA/hAT $F_1$ & Train/val disjoint? \\
\midrule
Stage 1 & v4.2 baseline (test) & 0.984 & 0.984 & 0.872 & --- & no \\
Stage 2 & v4.2-fix (epoch 28) & 0.925 & 0.895 & 0.604 & 0.265 & no (rotating-CV) \\
Stage 2 & v4.3-fix (epoch 40) & 0.984 & 0.982 & 0.727 & 0.919 & no (rotating-CV) \\
Stage 3 & v4.3-singlefold (ep.~28) & 0.959 & 0.955 & 0.638 & 0.256 & yes \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Side-by-side summary of the three stages on the species-disjoint Pantera test set. v4.3-singlefold is the only variant whose train and validation species are disjoint for the whole run. The DNA/hAT collapse from $0.92$ (v4.3-fix) to $0.26$ (v4.3-singlefold and v4.2-fix) shows that the apparent Stage-2 superfamily strength was largely a side-effect of the inner-CV rotation rather than an architectural property.}
\label{tab:stage_compare}
\end{table}


