\subsection{Mini-Benchmark on Three Excised Amniote Genomes}\label{ssec:mini_benchmark}

\subsubsection{Benchmark Species}

The three held-out species span the main amniote lineages (Table~\ref{tab:mini_benchmark_species}): zebra finch (\textit{T.~guttata}, Aves), platypus (\textit{O.~anatinus}, Mammalia), and American alligator (\textit{A.~mississippiensis}, Reptilia). Each species has a curated RepeatMasker-format TE library serving as the primary ground-truth set; structural LTR sequences detected by genome-wide terminal-repeat alignment provide additional LTR-class coverage. The Stage-2 v4.3-fix and Stage-3 v4.3-singlefold checkpoints are evaluated; only sequences whose top-level class is DNA, LTR, or LINE are scored, and superfamily metrics are restricted further to entries whose tag is in the model's 23-SF vocabulary. v4.2-fix is omitted because its training set did not exclude the benchmark genomes.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{llccc}
\hline
Species & Lineage & Pantera consensi & Curated library & Structural LTR seqs \\
\hline
\textit{T. guttata} (Zebra finch) & Aves & 161 & 543 & 6{,}480 \\
\textit{O. anatinus} (Platypus) & Mammalia & 25 & 380 & 49{,}814 \\
\textit{A. mississippiensis} (Alligator) & Reptilia & 296 & 1{,}196 & 15{,}557 \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\caption{Mini-benchmark species and their associated datasets. Pantera consensi are sequences identified by the Pantera pipeline in each species' genome. The curated library is the externally curated RepeatMasker-format TE reference library used as the primary evaluation set. Structural LTR sequences are confirmed LTR-class elements detected by genome-wide LTR-terminal-repeat alignment, carrying genomic coordinate metadata but no superfamily annotation.}
\label{tab:mini_benchmark_species}
\end{table}

\subsubsection{Stage 2 vs Stage 3 on the Mini-Benchmark}

Table~\ref{tab:mini_benchmark} summarises the headline numbers. The Stage-2 v4.3-fix checkpoint reaches an overall three-class macro $F_1$ of $0.763$ and a superfamily macro $F_1$ of $0.231$; the Stage-3 v4.3-singlefold checkpoint reaches $0.607$ at the class level and $0.250$ at the superfamily level. The class-level advantage of Stage~2 over Stage~3 ($+0.156$) is in the same direction and roughly the same magnitude as the corresponding gap on the Pantera test set (Section~\ref{ssec:stage3}), and at the superfamily level the gap reverses sign ($-0.019$ in Stage~2's favour becomes $+0.019$ in Stage~3's favour). The natural reading is that Stage~2's apparent class-level superiority reflects checkpoint selection on a contaminated validation set rather than a real generalisation gain; on truly unseen genomes, the two leak-controlled measurements agree to within a few hundredths at the superfamily level.

