\label{tab:mini_benchmark_perclass}
\end{table}

\paragraph{Interpretation.} The mini-benchmark sharpens the diagnostic from the Pantera test split: the dominant failure mode in this project is not classical val/test overfitting but \emph{species-shift}. Stages~2 and~3 differ noticeably in superfamily $F_1$ on the species-disjoint Pantera test ($0.727$ vs $0.638$), but on truly unseen amniote genomes the two land within a few hundredths of each other ($0.231$ vs $0.250$); the apparent gain of training under the rotating CV simply does not transfer. The per-class breakdown attributes most of the residual error budget to LTR sequence features and, on zebra finch, additionally to DNA. The pre-split-fix figures originally generated under the Stage-1 v4.3 random hold-out (transfer class accuracy, per-superfamily heatmap, transfer error analysis, transfer confusion matrices, in-distribution misclassification analysis) have been retired; equivalent figures for v4.3-singlefold are flagged for inclusion in the final draft (Section~\ref{ssec:limitations}).

\clearpage
\subsection{Saliency as a Sanity Check}\label{ssec:saliency}

\textit{Caveat.} The saliency analysis below was generated on the v4-era encoder trained under the Stage-1 random split (Section~\ref{ssec:stage1}), \emph{before} the Stage-2 / Stage-3 split-fix pipeline of Section~\ref{ssec:splits}. It is retained as an illustrative sanity check on the encoder family rather than as evidence about the species-disjoint models; re-running it on the Stage-3 v4.3-singlefold encoder is flagged in Section~\ref{ssec:limitations}.

Gradient-based saliency \cite{simonyan2014deep} serves as a qualitative check on which sequence regions drive predictions, not as causal attribution. For each test sequence, the $\ell_2$-normalised input gradient $\nabla_x L$ is computed; positive values flag positions that increase the true-class logit. 

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{saliency_analysis.png}
\caption{Occlusion-based saliency for four representative misclassified test sequences from the dominant within-class superfamily confusion pairs (DNA/hAT$\rightarrow$DNA, LTR/Gypsy$\rightarrow$LTR/Pao, DNA$\rightarrow$DNA/hAT, LINE/L1$\rightarrow$LINE/L1-Tx1) identified on the v4-era Stage-1 test set. For each example, two curves show the per-position drop in the true-class logit (blue) and in the predicted-class logit (orange) when a sliding window is masked, so positive values mark regions important for the corresponding class. A confident error like LINE/L1$\rightarrow$LINE/L1-Tx1 typically shows broadly negative true-class saliency across the body, while ambiguous within-class errors (LTR/Gypsy$\leftrightarrow$LTR/Pao) show overlapping true- and predicted-class envelopes consistent with shared internal motifs.}
\label{fig:saliency_analysis}
\end{figure}

Figure~\ref{fig:saliency_analysis} examines four representative misclassified sequences. For the within-class LTR/Gypsy$\rightarrow$LTR/Pao confusion, the true- and predicted-class attribution envelopes overlap, indicating shared internal motifs; for LINE/L1$\rightarrow$LINE/L1-Tx1, true-class saliency is broadly negative, consistent with a confident subfamily flip. These are illustrative cases; aggregated correct-vs-misclassified comparisons were not performed, so the pattern remains a hypothesis.

\subsection{Semi-supervised Clustering of TE Sequences}\label{ssec:clustering}

\textit{Caveat.} The v5 contrastive embedding below was fine-tuned from the v4-era Stage-1 encoder, before the Stage-2 / Stage-3 split-fix pipeline. Because the encoder it was initialised from has now been superseded by v4.3-singlefold, the clustering geometry should be read as an illustrative analysis of the encoder family rather than as a quantitative evaluation of the final classifier. A v5 rerun starting from the v4.3-singlefold encoder is left as future work (Section~\ref{ssec:limitations}).

The v5 semi-supervised contrastive model (Section~\ref{ssec:methods_family}) is evaluated here for its embedding geometry and clustering structure.

\subsubsection{Embedding Space Geometry}

After training, embeddings were assessed using per-superfamily centroid $L_2$ distances and UMAP projections \cite{mcginnis2021umap}. Per-superfamily compactness varies with internal sequence heterogeneity (Table~\ref{tab:l2_compactness}): superfamilies with stereotyped sequence features show low mean centroid $L_2$ (e.g., DNA/PiggyBac, 1.84), while superfamilies with high internal diversity show larger spread (e.g., DNA/hAT, 3.71). The UMAP projection of the combined-loss model shows partial superfamily-level ordering within the DNA class, with hAT and TcMar-Tc1 elements occupying distinct regions.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lrr}
\toprule
Superfamily & $n$ & Mean centroid $L_2$ \\
\midrule
DNA/PiggyBac      & 237  & 1.84 \\
DNA/Academ-1      & 148  & 2.35 \\
DNA/TcMar-Tc1     & 561  & 2.38 \\
DNA/PIF-Harbinger & 273  & 2.48 \\
DNA/CMC           & 112  & 3.05 \\
DNA/hAT           & 1{,}882 & 3.71 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Per-superfamily embedding compactness in the v5 contrastive model, measured as mean $L_2$ distance from each sequence to its superfamily centroid (subsampled to 200 per superfamily where $n > 200$). Lower values indicate more compact, stereotyped clusters. Since v5 was trained specifically on DNA transposons, only the six DNA superfamilies present in the embedding space are reported.}
\label{tab:l2_compactness}
\end{table}

\subsubsection{Hierarchical Clustering and Subclusters}

To identify structure within classes, HDBSCAN was applied to the DNA transposon embeddings (72 clusters; Figure~\ref{fig:clustering_umap}), and agglomerative hierarchical clustering (Ward linkage \cite{ward1963hierarchical}) was applied across all classes, yielding 252 subclusters from 7,966 sequences. Agreement with annotated superfamily labels is modest (ARI~=~0.036, NMI~=~0.136, homogeneity~=~0.247, completeness~=~0.094): individual clusters are superfamily-specific, but each superfamily is fragmented across many clusters, consistent with the model discovering finer-grained sequence subvariants rather than reproducing annotation boundaries.

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{contrastive_training.png}
\caption{Training history for the v5 contrastive model (combined SupCon + cross-entropy + center loss). The combined objective stabilises the embedding geometry compared to pure SupCon, preventing arbitrary inter-superfamily separation while maintaining cluster compactness.}
\label{fig:contrastive_training}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{contrastive_umap.png}
\caption{UMAP projection of contrastive learning embeddings (v5 combined-loss model). The model recovers class-level structure (DNA/LTR/LINE), with partial superfamily ordering visible within each cluster. Note that UMAP axes have no direct biological interpretation; the 2D layout preserves local neighbourhood structure in the high-dimensional embedding space.}
\label{fig:contrastive_umap}
\end{figure}

\subsubsection{UMAP Visualization and Interpretability}

Two UMAP projections (Figures~\ref{fig:superfamily_umap} and~\ref{fig:contrastive_umap}) confirm class-level separation in the supervised embedding and partial superfamily ordering within the DNA class in the contrastive embedding. UMAP axes have no direct biological interpretation; only local neighbourhood structure is preserved.

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{superfamily_umap.png}
\caption{UMAP projection of V4 hybrid model embeddings coloured by top-level TE class. DNA transposons (blue), LTR/retrotransposons (pink), LINE/SINE elements (green), and unannotated sequences (grey) form broadly separated regions, demonstrating that the supervised embedding space captures coarse TE class structure. Overlapping regions reflect sequences near class boundaries or with ambiguous annotations. UMAP axes have no direct biological interpretation; the 2D layout preserves local neighbourhood structure in the high-dimensional embedding space.}
\label{fig:superfamily_umap}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{clustering_umap.png}
\caption{UMAP projection of DNA transposon embeddings coloured by HDBSCAN cluster identity. The top 20 largest clusters are shown in distinct colours; remaining points are shown in light grey. A total of 72 clusters were discovered, revealing substantial substructure within the DNA transposon class beyond the seven annotated superfamilies. Spatially isolated clusters suggest the model has learned sequence groupings that may correspond to novel biological subfamilies or convergently-evolved sequence variants. UMAP axes have no direct biological interpretation.}
\label{fig:clustering_umap}
\end{figure}

\subsubsection{Novel Substructure Discovery}

Of the 72 HDBSCAN clusters, the ten largest with dominant superfamily fraction $<$80\% are listed in Table~\ref{tab:novel_subclusters}. Seven have Unknown as the top or second annotation, consistent with the model capturing sequence groupings not yet assigned to a named superfamily by the Pantera pipeline.

