% ============ DISCUSSION ============
\clearpage
\section{Discussion}

\subsection{The Three-Stage Lesson: Splits, Not Architectures}\label{ssec:disc_stages}

The single clearest finding of the project is that, holding the hybrid architecture fixed, the choice of data-split protocol changes the headline numbers by far more than any modelling decision did. Stage~1 (random hold-out) gave the most flattering numbers (v4.2 three-class test $F_1 = 0.984$, sf $F_1 = 0.872$) but with a 0.13 val/test gap that was already a quantitative warning of species leakage. Stage~2 (species-disjoint outer split with rotating-CV inner) gave the best species-disjoint Pantera test numbers (v4.3-fix class $F_1 = 0.982$, sf $F_1 = 0.727$) but inflated the validation signal --- val sf $F_1$ reached $\approx 1.0$ by late epochs --- because each fold's val species were recycled back into training; the price of relying on this val for early stopping was the $0.92$ DNA/hAT score, which collapsed to $0.26$ once the rotation was removed. Stage~3 (single-fold inner split) is the only setting in which val and test agree (val sf $F_1 \approx 0.70$ vs test $0.638$) and is therefore the only setting in which the validation signal can be trusted for checkpoint selection. The pattern is not specific to this thesis: in any species-grouped sequence-classification problem, a rotating-CV inner schedule combined with a species-grouped outer test will produce Stage-2-shaped results --- a clean test set but a contaminated validation signal --- and the $0.092$ residual sf-$F_1$ gap to Stage~3 should be expected as the cost of repairing it. The three-stage progression also suggests a re-reading of Stage~1: rather than reporting it as ``the in-distribution baseline'', it is more useful to report it as a label-quality audit \cite{northcutt2021confident} in the spirit of confident-learning and of established RepeatMasker / Dfam curation cycles \cite{storer2021dfam,flynn2020repeatmodeler2}.

\subsection{Species-Shift, Not Classical Overfitting, is the Dominant Failure Mode}\label{ssec:disc_species_shift}

A natural reading of Stage~1 alone would attribute the val/test gap to classical overfitting and prescribe more regularisation, more data augmentation or smaller models. The Stages~2 and~3 mini-benchmark results (Section~\ref{ssec:mini_benchmark}) make a stronger claim: the dominant failure mode in this project is \emph{species-shift}. Three observations support this. First, when the rotating-CV inner schedule is removed in Stage~3, the species-disjoint Pantera test sf $F_1$ drops by $0.089$ but the mini-benchmark sf $F_1$ \emph{rises} slightly ($0.231 \to 0.250$); training under the rotating CV inflates in-distribution numbers without buying any out-of-distribution generalisation. Second, the per-class transfer profile (Table~\ref{tab:mini_benchmark_perclass}) is strongly lineage-dependent under both stages: platypus generalises best, alligator second, zebra finch worst, with DNA $F_1$ in zebra finch falling to $0.40$ and LTR $F_1$ collapsing to $0.21$--$0.50$ across all three species. The avian-specific ERV families that dominate zebra finch LTR mass simply do not have analogues in the trainval pool. Third, the DNA/hAT collapse documented in Section~\ref{ssec:stage3} is shared by both leak-controlled variants (v4.2-fix and v4.3-singlefold land within $0.01$ of each other on hAT despite very different val schedules), suggesting the limit there is not val-set memorisation but a genuine inability of a 23-way flat softmax over consensus sequence to separate hAT subvariants from a heterogeneous generic-DNA catch-all. The natural remedies are not stronger regularisation but broader phylogenetic training coverage, domain-adversarial training \cite{ganin2015unsupervised}, or pre-training on a much larger DNA corpus before fine-tuning on Pantera; meta-learning across species \cite{finn2017model} would be a complementary direction for low-shot lineages.

\subsection{When the GNN Branch Helps}\label{ssec:hybrid_disc}

The GNN branch contributes a clear improvement on the top-level task --- binary v4 (Section~\ref{ssec:hybrid}) and three-way v4.3 (Section~\ref{ssec:stage2}) --- but not on within-class superfamily discrimination. The attention gate is highly variable in the binary setting and converges to GNN weight $\approx 0.72$ from $\approx$ epoch 25 in the three-way setting, exactly tracking the standalone $k$-mer baseline (class-level macro $F_1 \approx 0.85$ vs near-chance within-class superfamily $F_1$ 0.064--0.097; Table~\ref{tab:kmer_within_class}). The gate is best read as a soft prior on which modality to trust: the GNN sees global composition, which is informative for top-level mechanism but not for the local motif differences that distinguish superfamilies, and the gate downweights it when the head asks a within-class question. A procedural detail also matters: late RC fusion (averaging strand embeddings before the head) is simpler and equally accurate compared to an early-fusion variant that symmetrises after the first convolutional layer, likely because early fusion forces filters to be RC-symmetric and therefore restricts the representable motif library.

\subsection{The Boundary-Prediction Diagnostic}\label{ssec:disc_boundary}

The most reproducible structural observation across all v1--v4.3 runs is from the auxiliary boundary-regression head. Sequence \emph{length} is recovered well ($r \approx 0.94$) but absolute canvas \emph{position} is not ($r \approx 0.07$--$0.18$). This is not a hyperparameter pathology --- it is a consequence of reading regression targets from a position-invariant masked global average pool, after which absolute placement information has been pooled away. The diagnostic is mainly useful as a design constraint for the v4.4 successor sketched in Section~\ref{ssec:limitations}: any model that needs to localise TE boundaries on a long canvas must inject a positional channel (sinusoidal or learned) before the pooling step, and probably needs a per-position segmentation head rather than a regression head reading from a pooled embedding.

\subsection{Limitations and Future Directions}\label{ssec:limitations}

\paragraph{Stage 1 is a label audit, not a generalisation estimate.} The Stage-1 hold-out is sequence-level random with class-balancing applied before the split (Section~\ref{ssec:splits}). Its test $F_1$ is therefore inflated for rare classes, and its primary value is as a label-quality check rather than a generalisation estimate. The Stage-3 mini-benchmark (Section~\ref{ssec:mini_benchmark}) provides the most realistic out-of-distribution numbers in the project.

\paragraph{Saliency and clustering use the pre-split-fix encoder.} The saliency analysis (Section~\ref{ssec:saliency}) and the v5 contrastive clustering (Section~\ref{ssec:clustering}) were both produced from the v4-era encoder trained under Stage~1. They are kept as illustrative analyses of the encoder family but should not be read as quantitative evidence about the species-disjoint models. Re-running both on the Stage-3 v4.3-singlefold encoder, and reporting the cluster--label correspondence on a species-disjoint test set, is the natural follow-up.

\paragraph{Mini-benchmark figures.} The per-superfamily transfer heatmap, error-bar analysis and confusion matrices originally generated under the Stage-1 v4.3 random hold-out have been retired from this draft because the underlying checkpoint is superseded; equivalent figures regenerated from v4.3-singlefold predictions on the mini-benchmark are pending.

\paragraph{v4.4: a position-aware successor.} The boundary-prediction diagnostic of Section~\ref{ssec:disc_boundary} motivates an in-progress v4.4 variant that adds sinusoidal positional channels to the input and replaces the regression head with a per-position segmentation head. If it improves localisation without harming classification, it is the natural successor to v4.3.

\paragraph{Beyond v4.4.} Three directions follow naturally from the species-shift framing of Section~\ref{ssec:disc_species_shift}: (i)~broader phylogenetic training coverage or domain-adversarial learning \cite{ganin2015unsupervised} to close the cross-species gap; (ii)~transposase and reverse-transcriptase domain features to disambiguate superfamilies that share nucleotide composition; and (iii)~DNA-sequence foundation models pre-trained at scale and fine-tuned on Pantera. Confident-learning style relabelling \cite{northcutt2021confident} of the Stage-1 disagreements would also tighten the underlying ground truth for any of these directions.

